From: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 23 May 2026 06:30:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] clk: qcom: rcg2: demote update-stuck WARN to ratelimited
 pr_warn

update_config() WARNs (with full backtrace) when CMD_UPDATE never
self-clears after a CFG write — but on IPQ5332 this is an EXPECTED
condition for the per-port uniphy RCGs (nss_cc_port{1,2}_{rx,tx}_clk_src)
at link-up time: their parent PCS UNIPHY clock is gated until the link
partner provides a recoverable RX clock, so an UPDATE issued before
link-stable can never sync. Hardware ignores the write; the RCG sits
at SRC_SEL=0=XO, matching vendor's running configuration.

Cost of the WARN: ~40 lines of arm64 backtrace per failure, dumped
through the 115200-baud serial console synchronously inside the
phylink_resolve workqueue. On `ip link set eth0 up` this fires twice
(RX + TX RCG) in immediate succession — ~5-6s of UART-blocked CPU
per WARN. With other prints already queued, the HW watchdog feeder
gets starved and the board hard-resets before link-up can finish.

Demote the WARN to pr_warn_ratelimited (no stack dump). The -EBUSY
return is unchanged; callers still see the failure and decide what
to do.

This is an OpenWrt-local change; not appropriate for upstream as-is
since other SoCs may legitimately want the stack-dump for non-IPQ
contexts. A proper upstream version would gate on a per-RCG flag.

Signed-off-by: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/clk/qcom/clk-rcg2.c
+++ b/drivers/clk/qcom/clk-rcg2.c
@@ -130,7 +130,12 @@ static int update_config(struct clk_rcg2 *rcg)
 		udelay(1);
 	}

-	WARN(1, "%s: rcg didn't update its configuration.", name);
+	/* On IPQ5332 the per-port uniphy RCGs intentionally fail to update
+	 * before link-stable (parent PCS clock gated). The original WARN
+	 * dumps a backtrace per failure which floods the serial console
+	 * and can starve the HW watchdog feeder — see commit log.
+	 */
+	pr_warn_ratelimited("%s: rcg didn't update its configuration.\n", name);
 	return -EBUSY;
 }

